    <label>word length <input is="query-param-input" data-query-param="wordLength" type="number" min="1" value="5"></label>
  </form>
</graph-loader>

<p>Each crossword answer has a certain number of vowels, shown on the x-axis, and has appeared a certain number of times in the puzzle, shown on the y-axis. Color represents how many answers there are with a given vowel count and frequency. Controlling for length, which <a href="/short-answer-is">we know affects frequency</a>, a pattern emerges. The low-frequency answers are concentrated around some middling number of vowels, often two to four. The high-frequency answers follow a similar distribution, but pushed a little bit towards more vowels. Which means the highest-frequency answers usually have one or two more vowels than is typical for their length.</p>

<h3>Revenge of the grid</h3>

<p>What actually makes these answers so...voweluable? It has to do with how the grid works, specifically the <a href="https://www.nytimes.com/puzzles/submissions/crossword">"interlocking" stipulation</a>. Some crossword traditions, namely the British style, encourage more spaced-out block squares. What you get is a grid where about half the letters in each answer are <em>uncrossed</em> by another answer, because they're sandwiched between two block squares. A seven-letter answer will only have three or four crosses. If you have all the crosses and still can't guess the answer, well, you're out of luck. American-style crosswords, on the other hand, generally stipulate that <em>every letter must be crossed</em>. That way, you have to be stumped by <em>two</em> answers, and intersecting ones at that, before you're really stuck.</p>

<p>Imagine you're writing a puzzle, and you need to choose an answer for 1-Across, the top left of the grid. Maybe you choose EXHORT. In a British-style crossword, you'd block off the squares under the second, fourth, and sixth letters. Now you just have to cross E, H, and R. This is great news because you were really dreading coming up with a word that started with X!</p>

<p>In an American-style puzzle, the grid gives you fewer places to hide inconvenient letters. You're stuck using every V, J, and Q. And as it turns out, vowels are especially bad. You need them all over the place to form actual words, but often they make for inconvenient crosses. Take a look at the distribution of vowels in crossword answers:</p>

<graph-loader data-id="vowelPlacement" data-src="api/figures/vowelPlacement">
  <form is="query-param-form">
    <label>word length <input is="query-param-input" data-query-param="wordLength" type="number" min="3" max="10" value="3"></label><br />
    <label>per-letter <input is="query-param-input" data-query-param="byPosition" type="checkbox"></label><br />
  </form>
</graph-loader>

<p>Each data point is a vowel distribution. For example, <code>--V</code> means a word that has two consonants then a vowel, like PHO. The x-axis represents the crossword "dictionary" -- how many possible answers there are for any given vowel distribution. The y-axis shows how many times an answer in the puzzle has used a certain vowel distribution (it's our old friend <a href="/short-answer-is#tokensAndTypes">tokens vs. types</a>). Let's say there are 100 three-letter words in the dictionary, and over the course of a year we use 1000 three-letter answers in our puzzles. Each three-letter word would be repeated on average ten times.</p>

<p>Check out <code>-V-</code>. The graph tells us that about a third of the 1000 three-letter puzzle answers have a consonant-vowel-consonant distribution. That's 333. It also says that, coincidentally, about a third of the 100 possible three-letter words to choose from have that same distribution. That's 33. We're choosing 333 answers from 33 possible words. So average repetition among <code>-V-</code> answers is 10, just what we'd expect if letter distribution among answers were even.</p>

<p>Now look at <code>V-V</code>. It looks like 18%, or 180, of our 1000 answers have a <code>V-V</code> distribution, but we're only choosing from 8%, or 8, of the 100 words in our dictionary. On average, answers with <code>V-V</code> distribution have to get repeated 22 times!</p>

<p>Distributions above the line have higher-than-average repetition. For any given length of word, distributions that start and end with vowels are above the line. What's going on here is that when you're constructing an American-style crossword and you choose PAELLA for 1-Across, you've now got to come up with three words that start with vowels. Probably the theme answer you already filled in three squares below has some vowels in it too, so one or two of those three might have to <em>end</em> with vowels as well. But there are only a handful of words like that to choose from! That's why 18 of the top 20 <a href="/short-answer-is#mostFrequentAnswers">most common crossword answers</a> start <em>and</em> end with A, E, I, or O.</p>

<h3>Filling is hard</h3>

<p>Here's another way to think about it. Remember, you're building a puzzle and choosing an answer for 1-Across. How many vowels will the answer have?</p>

<graph-loader data-id="vowelsByLength" data-src="api/figures/vowelsByLength"></graph-loader>

<p>It depends on answer length, of course, but say you pick an answer with two vowels. You've now committed yourself to finding two <em>down</em> answers that <em>start</em> with vowels. What percent of answers have a vowel in any given letter position (assuming the answer you choose is long enough)?</p>

<graph-loader data-id="vowelPositions" data-src="api/figures/vowelPositions"></graph-loader>

<p>It should come as no surprise that relatively few answers start with a vowel. It's the same old story -- there's a high demand and low supply.</p>

<p>Now imagine you're picking another across answer, and you want to put it somewhere below 1-Across. The graph says there's about a 36% chance that 1-Across and the new answer <em>both</em> have vowels in the second position. If they do, suddenly your options for 2-Down are looking tough! Say you put the new across in the second row, just below 1-Across. Now 2-Down has to start with two consecutive vowels, which doesn't feel good. So maybe you put the new across a few squares below 1-Across, in the fourth row, and you move on to the downs. If you want the downs to have length four, then 2-Down has to start and end with vowels, which is <em>also</em> hard to fill! So you start thinking about maybe moving it up a row and oh geez now your head is hurting and it's time for a break. Just by choosing those two answers together, you've established a lot about the fill and/or the shape of the northwest corner.</p>

<h3>The grid speaks</h3>

<p>Don't believe me? Here's a heatmap of where vowels appear in 15x15 puzzles:</p>

<graph-loader data-id="vowelsGrid" data-src="api/figures/vowelsGrid" data-square="true"></graph-loader>

<p>There's your headache, clear as day in the northwest corner. We know that vowels often show up in an answer's second letter. And the second letters of 1-Across and 1-Down have the highest vowel frequency in the grid! There's almost never a block square in the top left corner, meaning two answers start there in almost every puzzle. We can look at where in the grid answers start:</p>

<graph-loader data-id="answerStartsGrid" data-src="api/figures/answerStartsGrid" data-square="true"></graph-loader>

<p>Of course answers start most frequently in the top row and left-most column. We can look at the words that go in those positions:</p>

<table-loader data-id="topLeftAnswers" data-src="api/figures/topLeftAnswers">
  <form is="query-param-form">
    <label>row/column <input is="query-param-input" data-query-param="gridIndex" type="number" value="2" min="1" max="15"></label>
  </form>
